We face a problem that sometimes prohibts us to automatically create a cassandra data model.

We have multiple UDTs in our project and they reference each other.

 - DocumentUDT references nothing
 - SmallProductUDT references DocumentUDT
 - BigProductUDT references SmallProduct (DocumentUDT transitively) and DocumentUDT explicitly
 - FinalProductUDT references BigProductUDT and a list of DocumentUDTs

As said before, sometimes the generation of the keyspace and the UDT types works like a charm. Sometimes not. We assume the reason is somewhere in the **CassandraPersistentEntitySchemaCreator**.

```
protected List&lt;CreateUserTypeSpecification&gt; createUserTypeSpecifications(boolean ifNotExists) {

		Collection&lt;? extends CassandraPersistentEntity&lt;?&gt;&gt; entities = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(
				this.mappingContext.getUserDefinedTypeEntities());

		Map&lt;CqlIdentifier, CassandraPersistentEntity&lt;?&gt;&gt; byTableName = entities.stream()
				.collect(Collectors.toMap(CassandraPersistentEntity::getTableName, entity -&gt; entity));

		List&lt;CreateUserTypeSpecification&gt; specifications = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();

		Set&lt;CqlIdentifier&gt; created = new HashSet&lt;&gt;();

		entities.forEach(entity -&gt; {

			Set&lt;CqlIdentifier&gt; seen = new LinkedHashSet&lt;&gt;();

			seen.add(entity.getTableName());
			visitUserTypes(entity, seen);

			List&lt;CqlIdentifier&gt; ordered = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;(seen);

			Collections.reverse(ordered);

			specifications.addAll(ordered
					.stream().filter(created::add).map(identifier -&gt; this.mappingContext
							.getCreateUserTypeSpecificationFor(byTableName.get(identifier)).ifNotExists(ifNotExists))
					.collect(Collectors.toList()));
		});

		return specifications;
	}

	private void visitUserTypes(CassandraPersistentEntity&lt;?&gt; entity, final Set&lt;CqlIdentifier&gt; seen) {

		for (CassandraPersistentProperty property : entity) {

			BasicCassandraPersistentEntity&lt;?&gt; persistentEntity = this.mappingContext.getPersistentEntity(property);

			if (persistentEntity == null) {
				continue;
			}

			if (persistentEntity.isUserDefinedType() &amp;&amp; seen.add(persistentEntity.getTableName())) {
				visitUserTypes(persistentEntity, seen);
			}
		}
	}

```

The internal order of the created *specifications* variable is crucial if the keyspace can be created. It is mandatory that the DocumentUDT is always created first.

However, *visitUserTypes()* is working with a Set-implementation and this is potentially destroying the order of the traversed nodes in the DFS. 
Afterwards, the returned set collection is reversed again but the given order is arbitrary anyway. 

Would it be helpful to use a queue structure for the seen UDTs and according to their order start the DFS search with the first element in the queue?

