[Everything in JavaScript is pass by value](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/518000/is-javascript-a-pass-by-reference-or-pass-by-value-language) however, it happens that the value of an object is its reference. However, the important thing here is that for primitives, will not get changes when a referenced variable changes:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var a = &quot;world&quot;;
    var obj = {
      b: &quot;hello&quot; + a //evaluated once
    }

    a = &quot;universe&quot;; //does not modify obj.b which references a

    console.log(obj.b); //helloworld

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

In order to have a dynamically evaluated string, you need to call a function or a method:

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var a = &quot;world&quot;;
    var obj = {
      b: function() { 
        return &quot;hello&quot; + a //evaluated every time the function is executed
      }
    }
    console.log(obj.b()); //helloworld

    a = &quot;universe&quot;; //will influence obj.b

    console.log(obj.b()); //hellouniverse

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

However, that looks a bit &quot;dirty&quot; since it forces the caller to know to evaluate the property every time. It can also introduce inconsistency if some properties are plain strings, others functions and it&#39;s especially annoying if a property has to change from one to the other - you need to modify every place that calls this code to change, say, `obj.c` to `obj.c()`.

Instead, using ES6+ you can [define a getter](https://stackoverflow.com/questions/7891937/is-it-possible-to-implement-dynamic-getters-setters-in-javascript/9265685#9265685) for a property that will do the same as before but will hide the function call, so any time you read a property you actually evaluate code to return the result:


&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    var a = &quot;world&quot;;
    var obj = {
      c: &quot;plain property&quot;
    }

    Object.defineProperty(obj, &#39;b&#39;, {
      get: function() {
        return &quot;hello&quot; + a //evaluated every time the property is read
      }
    });

    console.log(obj.b); //helloworld

    a = &quot;universe&quot;; //will influence obj.b

    console.log(obj.b); //hellouniverse
    console.log(obj.c); //plain property

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

